### Description

It would be great if the `atom-text-editor` element sized itself according to its contents. We rely on this behavior in Nuclide to provide syntax highlighting inside [type-hints](https://nuclide.io/docs/languages/flow/#type-hinting), which uses an atom-text-editor inside a marker overlay. This used to work fine in Atom ≤1.8.x, although it relied on the `min-width: 1em` trick documented in the init script below. In 1.9.x, `.lines` elements inside the atom-text-editor shadow DOM don't have an explicit pixel width set anymore, which causes this behavior to break.

Ideally there would be an attribute that would make the text editor reliably auto-size itself according to its contents.
### Steps to Reproduce

Use the following init script (`init.js` in ~/.atom):

``` es6
'use babel';

import {TextBuffer} from 'atom';

function setupTextEditor(props) {
  const textEditorParams = {
    buffer: props.textBuffer,
    lineNumberGutterVisible: false,
  };
  const textEditor = atom.workspace.buildTextEditor(textEditorParams);
  if (props.grammar != null) {
    textEditor.setGrammar(props.grammar);
  }
  return textEditor;
}

async function setup() {
  const buffer = new TextBuffer('const f = {a: 123};'); // dummy JS code
  const [jsGrammar] = atom.grammars.getGrammars().filter(g => g.name === 'JavaScript'); // hack to get JS grammar
  const textEditor = await atom.workspace.open();
  const range = textEditor.setText('test');
  const marker = textEditor.markBufferRange(range, {invalidate: 'never'});
  const datatipElement = document.createElement('div');
  const floatingEditor = setupTextEditor({
    grammar: jsGrammar,
    textBuffer: buffer,
  }); // floatingEditor is expected to size itself according to ints contents.
  datatipElement.style.border = '1px solid red';
  datatipElement.style.minWidth = '1em'; // hack to auto-size in 1.8.x and prior. Auto-sizing does not work in 1.9.x
  datatipElement.appendChild(floatingEditor.getElement());
  textEditor.decorateMarker(
    marker,
    {
      type: 'overlay',
      position: 'tail',
      item: datatipElement,
    },
  );
  return datatipElement;
}
atom.packages.onDidActivateInitialPackages(setup); // wait for grammar package to activate
```

**Expected behavior:**
1.8.x: The text-editor element (highlighted with red border) expands to fit its contents:
<img width="327" alt="screenshot 2016-08-16 18 28 15" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/632968/17721528/ad35a52e-63df-11e6-8ae3-03f6c8d9ee4c.png">

**Actual behavior:**
1.9.x: text-editor element does not set its width; it is `0` by default (1em in the screenshot due to applying the `min-width: 1em` trick):
<img width="455" alt="screenshot 2016-08-16 18 28 34" src="https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/632968/17721526/a9aaff3a-63df-11e6-8c86-c8fabfdc8dfe.png">
### Versions

Broken in ≥ 1.9.x.

Pass the menu item when executing menu command so that we could know exactly which menu item triggers the event by interrogating event.detail property.

E.g., Inside a package

``` js
this.subscriptions = new CompositeDisposable();
this.subscriptions.add(atom.commands.add("atom-workspace", {
  "some-command": (evt) => {
    console.log(evt.detail);  // detail should be menu item
  }
});
```
